{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":950,"text":"Now, extinction is a different kind of death."},{"time":6012,"text":"It's bigger."},{"time":8635,"text":"We didn't really realize that until 1914,"},{"time":11715,"text":"when the last passenger pigeon, a female named Martha,"},{"time":14930,"text":"died at the Cincinnati zoo."},{"time":17948,"text":"This had been the most abundant bird in the world"},{"time":21489,"text":"that'd been in North America for six million years."},{"time":25096,"text":"Suddenly it wasn't here at all."},{"time":28401,"text":"Flocks that were a mile wide and 400 miles long"},{"time":32478,"text":"used to darken the sun."},{"time":35125,"text":"Aldo Leopold said this was a biological storm,"},{"time":38195,"text":"a feathered tempest."},{"time":41000,"text":"And indeed it was a keystone species"},{"time":43444,"text":"that enriched the entire eastern deciduous forest,"},{"time":47460,"text":"from the Mississippi to the Atlantic,"},{"time":49744,"text":"from Canada down to the Gulf."},{"time":53059,"text":"But it went from five billion birds to zero in just a couple decades."},{"time":56372,"text":"What happened?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":57572,"text":"Well, commercial hunting happened."},{"time":59725,"text":"These birds were hunted for meat that was sold by the ton,"},{"time":63684,"text":"and it was easy to do because when those big flocks"},{"time":66004,"text":"came down to the ground, they were so dense"},{"time":68276,"text":"that hundreds of hunters and netters could show up"},{"time":70644,"text":"and slaughter them by the tens of thousands."},{"time":73650,"text":"It was the cheapest source of protein in America."},{"time":76668,"text":"By the end of the century, there was nothing left"},{"time":78643,"text":"but these beautiful skins in museum specimen drawers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":83483,"text":"There's an upside to the story."},{"time":85358,"text":"This made people realize that the same thing"},{"time":87272,"text":"was about to happen to the American bison,"},{"time":89764,"text":"and so these birds saved the buffalos."}]},{"cues":[{"time":93169,"text":"But a lot of other animals weren't saved."},{"time":94843,"text":"The Carolina parakeet was a parrot that lit up backyards everywhere."},{"time":99634,"text":"It was hunted to death for its feathers."},{"time":101980,"text":"There was a bird that people liked on the East Coast called the heath hen."},{"time":105082,"text":"It was loved. They tried to protect it. It died anyway."},{"time":108091,"text":"A local newspaper spelled out, \"There is no survivor,"},{"time":111465,"text":"there is no future, there is no life to be recreated in this form ever again.\""},{"time":116282,"text":"There's a sense of deep tragedy that goes with these things,"},{"time":118953,"text":"and it happened to lots of birds that people loved."},{"time":121378,"text":"It happened to lots of mammals."},{"time":123586,"text":"Another keystone species is a famous animal"},{"time":126209,"text":"called the European aurochs."},{"time":128274,"text":"There was sort of a movie made about it recently."},{"time":130729,"text":"And the aurochs was like the bison."},{"time":133337,"text":"This was an animal that basically kept the forest"},{"time":136517,"text":"mixed with grasslands across the entire Europe and Asian continent,"},{"time":141569,"text":"from Spain to Korea."},{"time":143913,"text":"The documentation of this animal goes back"},{"time":146041,"text":"to the Lascaux cave paintings."}]},{"cues":[{"time":149266,"text":"The extinctions still go on."},{"time":151458,"text":"There's an ibex in Spain called the bucardo."},{"time":154487,"text":"It went extinct in 2000."},{"time":156833,"text":"There was a marvelous animal, a marsupial wolf"},{"time":159590,"text":"called the thylacine in Tasmania, south of Australia,"},{"time":163321,"text":"called the Tasmanian tiger."},{"time":165391,"text":"It was hunted until there were just a few left to die in zoos."},{"time":169709,"text":"A little bit of film was shot."}]},{"cues":[{"time":183593,"text":"Sorrow, anger, mourning."},{"time":188850,"text":"Don't mourn. Organize."},{"time":192006,"text":"What if you could find out that, using the DNA in museum specimens,"},{"time":195625,"text":"fossils maybe up to 200,000 years old"},{"time":198622,"text":"could be used to bring species back,"},{"time":201060,"text":"what would you do? Where would you start?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":202684,"text":"Well, you'd start by finding out if the biotech is really there."},{"time":205598,"text":"I started with my wife, Ryan Phelan,"},{"time":207690,"text":"who ran a biotech business called DNA Direct,"},{"time":210824,"text":"and through her, one of her colleagues, George Church,"},{"time":214873,"text":"one of the leading genetic engineers"},{"time":217568,"text":"who turned out to be also obsessed with passenger pigeons"},{"time":220577,"text":"and a lot of confidence"},{"time":222188,"text":"that methodologies he was working on"},{"time":224500,"text":"might actually do the deed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":226589,"text":"So he and Ryan organized and hosted a meeting"},{"time":229844,"text":"at the Wyss Institute in Harvard bringing together"},{"time":232108,"text":"specialists on passenger pigeons, conservation ornithologists, bioethicists,"},{"time":236719,"text":"and fortunately passenger pigeon DNA had already been sequenced"},{"time":240832,"text":"by a molecular biologist named Beth Shapiro."},{"time":244123,"text":"All she needed from those specimens at the Smithsonian"},{"time":247002,"text":"was a little bit of toe pad tissue,"},{"time":249657,"text":"because down in there is what is called ancient DNA."},{"time":253040,"text":"It's DNA which is pretty badly fragmented,"},{"time":256012,"text":"but with good techniques now, you can basically reassemble the whole genome."}]},{"cues":[{"time":260904,"text":"Then the question is, can you reassemble,"},{"time":263225,"text":"with that genome, the whole bird?"},{"time":265720,"text":"George Church thinks you can."},{"time":268224,"text":"So in his book, \"Regenesis,\" which I recommend,"},{"time":271289,"text":"he has a chapter on the science of bringing back extinct species,"},{"time":274752,"text":"and he has a machine called"},{"time":276288,"text":"the Multiplex Automated Genome Engineering machine."},{"time":279736,"text":"It's kind of like an evolution machine."},{"time":281470,"text":"You try combinations of genes that you write"},{"time":284176,"text":"at the cell level and then in organs on a chip,"},{"time":287416,"text":"and the ones that win, that you can then put"},{"time":289325,"text":"into a living organism. It'll work."},{"time":292022,"text":"The precision of this, one of George's famous unreadable slides,"},{"time":295216,"text":"nevertheless points out that there's a level of precision here"},{"time":299815,"text":"right down to the individual base pair."},{"time":302381,"text":"The passenger pigeon has 1.3 billion base pairs in its genome."}]},{"cues":[{"time":306520,"text":"So what you're getting is the capability now"},{"time":309525,"text":"of replacing one gene with another variation of that gene."},{"time":313050,"text":"It's called an allele."},{"time":314953,"text":"Well that's what happens in normal hybridization anyway."},{"time":317803,"text":"So this is a form of synthetic hybridization of the genome"},{"time":320994,"text":"of an extinct species"},{"time":322874,"text":"with the genome of its closest living relative."},{"time":326404,"text":"Now along the way, George points out that"},{"time":329119,"text":"his technology, the technology of synthetic biology,"},{"time":332930,"text":"is currently accelerating at four times the rate of Moore's Law."},{"time":336736,"text":"It's been doing that since 2005, and it's likely to continue."}]},{"cues":[{"time":341024,"text":"Okay, the closest living relative of the passenger pigeon"},{"time":343728,"text":"is the band-tailed pigeon. They're abundant. There's some around here."},{"time":347022,"text":"Genetically, the band-tailed pigeon already is"},{"time":351110,"text":"mostly living passenger pigeon."},{"time":353478,"text":"There's just some bits that are band-tailed pigeon."},{"time":355913,"text":"If you replace those bits with passenger pigeon bits,"},{"time":358657,"text":"you've got the extinct bird back, cooing at you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":362872,"text":"Now, there's work to do."},{"time":364780,"text":"You have to figure out exactly what genes matter."},{"time":367494,"text":"So there's genes for the short tail in the band-tailed pigeon,"},{"time":370136,"text":"genes for the long tail in the passenger pigeon,"},{"time":372836,"text":"and so on with the red eye, peach-colored breast, flocking, and so on."},{"time":376394,"text":"Add them all up and the result won't be perfect."},{"time":379265,"text":"But it should be be perfect enough,"},{"time":381243,"text":"because nature doesn't do perfect either."}]},{"cues":[{"time":383889,"text":"So this meeting in Boston led to three things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":388065,"text":"First off, Ryan and I decided to create a nonprofit"},{"time":391611,"text":"called Revive and Restore that would push de-extinction generally"},{"time":395264,"text":"and try to have it go in a responsible way,"},{"time":398415,"text":"and we would push ahead with the passenger pigeon."}]},{"cues":[{"time":401703,"text":"Another direct result was a young grad student named Ben Novak,"},{"time":405768,"text":"who had been obsessed with passenger pigeons since he was 14"},{"time":409024,"text":"and had also learned how to work with ancient DNA,"},{"time":412087,"text":"himself sequenced the passenger pigeon,"},{"time":415398,"text":"using money from his family and friends."},{"time":418013,"text":"We hired him full-time."},{"time":420160,"text":"Now, this photograph I took of him last year at the Smithsonian,"},{"time":423824,"text":"he's looking down at Martha,"},{"time":426055,"text":"the last passenger pigeon alive."},{"time":428840,"text":"So if he's successful, she won't be the last."}]},{"cues":[{"time":431575,"text":"The third result of the Boston meeting was the realization"},{"time":434457,"text":"that there are scientists all over the world"},{"time":436290,"text":"working on various forms of de-extinction,"},{"time":438264,"text":"but they'd never met each other."},{"time":440079,"text":"And National Geographic got interested"},{"time":442063,"text":"because National Geographic has the theory that"},{"time":444546,"text":"the last century, discovery was basically finding things,"},{"time":447919,"text":"and in this century, discovery is basically making things."},{"time":451996,"text":"De-extinction falls in that category."},{"time":453820,"text":"So they hosted and funded this meeting. And 35 scientists,"},{"time":457654,"text":"they were conservation biologists and molecular biologists,"},{"time":460934,"text":"basically meeting to see if they had work to do together."},{"time":464350,"text":"Some of these conservation biologists are pretty radical."},{"time":466716,"text":"There's three of them who are not just re-creating ancient species,"},{"time":470278,"text":"they're recreating extinct ecosystems"},{"time":473399,"text":"in northern Siberia, in the Netherlands, and in Hawaii."}]},{"cues":[{"time":477267,"text":"Henri, from the Netherlands,"},{"time":479542,"text":"with a Dutch last name I won't try to pronounce,"},{"time":482233,"text":"is working on the aurochs."},{"time":484478,"text":"The aurochs is the ancestor of all domestic cattle,"},{"time":488831,"text":"and so basically its genome is alive, it's just unevenly distributed."},{"time":494405,"text":"So what they're doing is working with seven breeds"},{"time":496819,"text":"of primitive, hardy-looking cattle like that Maremmana primitivo on the top there"},{"time":501574,"text":"to rebuild, over time, with selective back-breeding,"},{"time":505039,"text":"the aurochs."},{"time":507102,"text":"Now, re-wilding is moving faster in Korea"},{"time":510135,"text":"than it is in America,"},{"time":511994,"text":"and so the plan is, with these re-wilded areas all over Europe,"},{"time":515654,"text":"they will introduce the aurochs to do its old job,"},{"time":518862,"text":"its old ecological role,"},{"time":520804,"text":"of clearing the somewhat barren, closed-canopy forest"},{"time":524063,"text":"so that it has these biodiverse meadows in it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":527874,"text":"Another amazing story"},{"time":529689,"text":"came from Alberto Fernández-Arias."},{"time":533087,"text":"Alberto worked with the bucardo in Spain."},{"time":536406,"text":"The last bucardo was a female named Celia"},{"time":539239,"text":"who was still alive, but then they captured her,"},{"time":543802,"text":"they got a little bit of tissue from her ear,"},{"time":546214,"text":"they cryopreserved it in liquid nitrogen,"},{"time":549398,"text":"released her back into the wild,"},{"time":551184,"text":"but a few months later, she was found dead under a fallen tree."},{"time":554934,"text":"They took the DNA from that ear,"},{"time":557542,"text":"they planted it as a cloned egg in a goat,"},{"time":560982,"text":"the pregnancy came to term,"},{"time":563056,"text":"and a live baby bucardo was born."},{"time":565271,"text":"It was the first de-extinction in history."}]},{"cues":[{"time":568119,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":571662,"text":"It was short-lived."},{"time":572889,"text":"Sometimes interspecies clones have respiration problems."},{"time":576527,"text":"This one had a malformed lung and died after 10 minutes,"},{"time":579568,"text":"but Alberto was confident that"},{"time":582648,"text":"cloning has moved along well since then,"},{"time":585048,"text":"and this will move ahead, and eventually"},{"time":586587,"text":"there will be a population of bucardos"},{"time":588594,"text":"back in the mountains in northern Spain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":591851,"text":"Cryopreservation pioneer of great depth is Oliver Ryder."},{"time":595677,"text":"At the San Diego zoo, his frozen zoo"},{"time":598064,"text":"has collected the tissues from over 1,000 species"},{"time":602015,"text":"over the last 35 years."},{"time":604993,"text":"Now, when it's frozen that deep,"},{"time":607024,"text":"minus 196 degrees Celsius,"},{"time":609744,"text":"the cells are intact and the DNA is intact."},{"time":612376,"text":"They're basically viable cells,"},{"time":614453,"text":"so someone like Bob Lanza at Advanced Cell Technology"},{"time":618081,"text":"took some of that tissue from an endangered animal"},{"time":621296,"text":"called the Javan banteng, put it in a cow,"},{"time":623490,"text":"the cow went to term, and what was born"},{"time":626540,"text":"was a live, healthy baby Javan banteng,"},{"time":631621,"text":"who thrived and is still alive."}]},{"cues":[{"time":635024,"text":"The most exciting thing for Bob Lanza"},{"time":637800,"text":"is the ability now to take any kind of cell"},{"time":640488,"text":"with induced pluripotent stem cells"},{"time":642936,"text":"and turn it into germ cells, like sperm and eggs."}]},{"cues":[{"time":646909,"text":"So now we go to Mike McGrew"},{"time":649192,"text":"who is a scientist at Roslin Institute in Scotland,"},{"time":652688,"text":"and Mike's doing miracles with birds."},{"time":654992,"text":"So he'll take, say, falcon skin cells, fibroblast,"},{"time":658512,"text":"turn it into induced pluripotent stem cells."},{"time":661300,"text":"Since it's so pluripotent, it can become germ plasm."},{"time":664730,"text":"He then has a way to put the germ plasm"},{"time":666986,"text":"into the embryo of a chicken egg"},{"time":670530,"text":"so that that chicken will have, basically,"},{"time":673801,"text":"the gonads of a falcon."},{"time":675642,"text":"You get a male and a female each of those,"},{"time":677556,"text":"and out of them comes falcons."},{"time":680497,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":682456,"text":"Real falcons out of slightly doctored chickens."}]},{"cues":[{"time":687581,"text":"Ben Novak was the youngest scientist at the meeting."},{"time":690058,"text":"He showed how all of this can be put together."},{"time":692487,"text":"The sequence of events: he'll put together the genomes"},{"time":695033,"text":"of the band-tailed pigeon and the passenger pigeon,"},{"time":697411,"text":"he'll take the techniques of George Church"},{"time":700361,"text":"and get passenger pigeon DNA,"},{"time":702642,"text":"the techniques of Robert Lanza and Michael McGrew,"},{"time":705327,"text":"get that DNA into chicken gonads,"},{"time":707586,"text":"and out of the chicken gonads get passenger pigeon eggs, squabs,"},{"time":711805,"text":"and now you're getting a population of passenger pigeons."}]},{"cues":[{"time":715291,"text":"It does raise the question of,"},{"time":717235,"text":"they're not going to have passenger pigeon parents"},{"time":719208,"text":"to teach them how to be a passenger pigeon."},{"time":721834,"text":"So what do you do about that?"},{"time":724090,"text":"Well birds are pretty hard-wired, as it happens,"},{"time":726763,"text":"so most of that is already in their DNA,"},{"time":729130,"text":"but to supplement it, part of Ben's idea"},{"time":731914,"text":"is to use homing pigeons"},{"time":733570,"text":"to help train the young passenger pigeons how to flock"},{"time":736740,"text":"and how to find their way to their old nesting grounds"},{"time":739474,"text":"and feeding grounds."}]},{"cues":[{"time":742623,"text":"There were some conservationists,"},{"time":744261,"text":"really famous conservationists like Stanley Temple,"},{"time":747337,"text":"who is one of the founders of conservation biology,"},{"time":749953,"text":"and Kate Jones from the IUCN, which does the Red List."},{"time":754609,"text":"They're excited about all this,"},{"time":756570,"text":"but they're also concerned that it might be competitive"},{"time":759073,"text":"with the extremely important efforts to protect"},{"time":762111,"text":"endangered species that are still alive,"},{"time":764321,"text":"that haven't gone extinct yet."},{"time":766167,"text":"You see, you want to work on protecting the animals out there."},{"time":768540,"text":"You want to work on getting the market for ivory in Asia down"},{"time":772769,"text":"so you're not using 25,000 elephants a year."}]},{"cues":[{"time":776647,"text":"But at the same time, conservation biologists are realizing"},{"time":779697,"text":"that bad news bums people out."},{"time":782281,"text":"And so the Red List is really important, keep track of"},{"time":785006,"text":"what's endangered and critically endangered, and so on."},{"time":788330,"text":"But they're about to create what they call a Green List,"},{"time":791355,"text":"and the Green List will have species that are doing fine, thank you,"},{"time":795737,"text":"species that were endangered, like the bald eagle,"},{"time":798041,"text":"but they're much better off now, thanks to everybody's good work,"},{"time":801656,"text":"and protected areas around the world"},{"time":803822,"text":"that are very, very well managed."},{"time":805583,"text":"So basically, they're learning how to build on good news."},{"time":809686,"text":"And they see reviving extinct species"},{"time":812797,"text":"as the kind of good news you might be able to build on."}]},{"cues":[{"time":815677,"text":"Here's a couple related examples."},{"time":819002,"text":"Captive breeding will be a major part of bringing back these species."},{"time":822213,"text":"The California condor was down to 22 birds in 1987."},{"time":825629,"text":"Everybody thought is was finished."},{"time":827338,"text":"Thanks to captive breeding at the San Diego Zoo,"},{"time":830158,"text":"there's 405 of them now, 226 are out in the wild."},{"time":834178,"text":"That technology will be used on de-extincted animals."},{"time":838387,"text":"Another success story is the mountain gorilla in Central Africa."},{"time":841854,"text":"In 1981, Dian Fossey was sure they were going extinct."},{"time":845237,"text":"There were just 254 left."},{"time":847270,"text":"Now there are 880. They're increasing in population"},{"time":850809,"text":"by three percent a year."},{"time":852902,"text":"The secret is, they have an eco-tourism program,"},{"time":856293,"text":"which is absolutely brilliant."},{"time":857962,"text":"So this photograph was taken last month by Ryan"},{"time":860597,"text":"with an iPhone."},{"time":863373,"text":"That's how comfortable these wild gorillas are with visitors."}]},{"cues":[{"time":867688,"text":"Another interesting project, though it's going to need some help,"},{"time":871423,"text":"is the northern white rhinoceros."},{"time":873334,"text":"There's no breeding pairs left."},{"time":875295,"text":"But this is the kind of thing that"},{"time":877465,"text":"a wide variety of DNA for this animal is available in the frozen zoo."},{"time":881605,"text":"A bit of cloning, you can get them back."}]},{"cues":[{"time":884400,"text":"So where do we go from here?"},{"time":886590,"text":"These have been private meetings so far."},{"time":888254,"text":"I think it's time for the subject to go public."},{"time":890911,"text":"What do people think about it?"},{"time":892378,"text":"You know, do you want extinct species back?"},{"time":894457,"text":"Do you want extinct species back?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":897309,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":902575,"text":"Tinker Bell is going to come fluttering down."},{"time":905071,"text":"It is a Tinker Bell moment,"},{"time":906285,"text":"because what are people excited about with this?"},{"time":908681,"text":"What are they concerned about?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":910732,"text":"We're also going to push ahead with the passenger pigeon."},{"time":913179,"text":"So Ben Novak, even as we speak, is joining the group"},{"time":916949,"text":"that Beth Shapiro has at UC Santa Cruz."},{"time":920270,"text":"They're going to work on the genomes"},{"time":921658,"text":"of the passenger pigeon and the band-tailed pigeon."},{"time":923945,"text":"As that data matures, they'll send it to George Church,"},{"time":927854,"text":"who will work his magic, get passenger pigeon DNA out of that."},{"time":931749,"text":"We'll get help from Bob Lanza and Mike McGrew"},{"time":934593,"text":"to get that into germ plasm that can go into chickens"},{"time":937660,"text":"that can produce passenger pigeon squabs"},{"time":940228,"text":"that can be raised by band-tailed pigeon parents,"},{"time":942692,"text":"and then from then on, it's passenger pigeons all the way,"},{"time":944948,"text":"maybe for the next six million years."},{"time":948084,"text":"You can do the same thing, as the costs come down,"},{"time":950399,"text":"for the Carolina parakeet, for the great auk,"},{"time":953621,"text":"for the heath hen, for the ivory-billed woodpecker,"},{"time":956416,"text":"for the Eskimo curlew, for the Caribbean monk seal,"},{"time":958522,"text":"for the woolly mammoth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":961388,"text":"Because the fact is, humans have made a huge hole"},{"time":963864,"text":"in nature in the last 10,000 years."},{"time":966954,"text":"We have the ability now,"},{"time":968993,"text":"and maybe the moral obligation, to repair some of the damage."},{"time":973857,"text":"Most of that we'll do by expanding and protecting wildlands,"},{"time":978405,"text":"by expanding and protecting"},{"time":980074,"text":"the populations of endangered species."},{"time":984601,"text":"But some species"},{"time":986756,"text":"that we killed off totally"},{"time":991939,"text":"we could consider bringing back"},{"time":995253,"text":"to a world that misses them."}]},{"cues":[{"time":998420,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1000630,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1011828,"text":"Chris Anderson: Thank you."},{"time":1013682,"text":"I've got a question."},{"time":1015494,"text":"So, this is an emotional topic. Some people stand."},{"time":1020244,"text":"I suspect there are some people out there sitting,"},{"time":1023100,"text":"kind of asking tormented questions, almost, about,"},{"time":1026109,"text":"well, wait, wait, wait, wait, wait, wait a minute,"},{"time":1028019,"text":"there's something wrong with mankind"},{"time":1031116,"text":"interfering in nature in this way."},{"time":1034596,"text":"There's going to be unintended consequences."},{"time":1038068,"text":"You're going to uncork some sort of Pandora's box"},{"time":1040845,"text":"of who-knows-what. Do they have a point?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1044831,"text":"Stewart Brand: Well, the earlier point is"},{"time":1046331,"text":"we interfered in a big way by making these animals go extinct,"},{"time":1049882,"text":"and many of them were keystone species,"},{"time":1052423,"text":"and we changed the whole ecosystem they were in"},{"time":1054932,"text":"by letting them go."},{"time":1056725,"text":"Now, there's the shifting baseline problem, which is,"},{"time":1059306,"text":"so when these things come back,"},{"time":1060844,"text":"they might replace some birds that are there"},{"time":1063135,"text":"that people really know and love."},{"time":1065529,"text":"I think that's, you know, part of how it'll work."},{"time":1068276,"text":"This is a long, slow process --"},{"time":1071161,"text":"One of the things I like about it, it's multi-generation."},{"time":1073395,"text":"We will get woolly mammoths back."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1075452,"text":"CA: Well it feels like both the conversation"},{"time":1077228,"text":"and the potential here are pretty thrilling."},{"time":1079516,"text":"Thank you so much for presenting. SB: Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1081230,"text":"CA: Thank you. (Applause)"}]}]}